---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="House Painters New Town | Heritage Precinct Specialists"
  description="House painters in New Town — Federation and Georgian heritage homes, conservation-sensitive repaints, AS 4361.2 lead-paint management on pre-1970 stock. Period-correct schemes. Free quote."
  canonical="https://hobarthousepainters.com.au/new-town/">

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">New Town &middot; Lenah Valley &middot; Mount Stuart &middot; North Hobart</span>
      <h1>House painters in <span class="accent">New Town</span>.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        New Town is one of Hobart&rsquo;s great heritage precincts &mdash;
        Federation and Georgian homes, period weatherboard and brick, much of it
        pre-1970 and carrying lead paint. These homes deserve conservation-sensitive
        repaints, lead-safe preparation and period-correct colour. That&rsquo;s
        the work we specialise in here.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Get a free quote</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why New Town</span>
      <h2>Painting New Town heritage homes.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <h3>A genuine heritage precinct.</h3>
        <p>
          New Town, Mount Stuart and the inner-north hold some of Hobart&rsquo;s
          finest period housing &mdash; Federation cottages, Georgian residences,
          decorative weatherboard with detailed fretwork, fascia and original
          window joinery. Parts of the area are heritage-sensitive, and a change
          of colour scheme on a listed place or within a City of Hobart heritage
          precinct can touch planning rules. A like-for-like repaint is usually
          fine; we&rsquo;ll flag whether your job is straightforward and keep the
          work sympathetic to the property&rsquo;s character either way. See
          <a href="/services/heritage-painting/">heritage &amp; weatherboard
          painting</a>.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Pre-1970 means lead paint.</h3>
        <p>
          Most New Town heritage homes predate 1970, so the existing paint is
          very likely <strong>lead-based</strong>. We prepare to AS 4361.2
          lead-safe practice &mdash; no dry sanding or power-stripping that
          throws lead dust into the air, soil and your home, proper containment,
          dust capture where surfaces must be abraded, and clean collection and
          disposal of debris. It protects your family and our crew, and it&rsquo;s
          the step a bargain quote tends to skip.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Conservation-sensitive technique.</h3>
        <p>
          Period detail rewards patience &mdash; careful preparation of old
          timber, repair and re-puttying, priming bare patches, and finishes
          suited to heritage substrates. We brush detailed trim, fretwork and
          joinery properly rather than spraying and running, so a Federation or
          Georgian home still reads as one when we&rsquo;re done.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Period-correct colour.</h3>
        <p>
          We can paint to an appropriate heritage scheme &mdash; the right body,
          trim and highlight colours for the period &mdash; and talk through
          options at the quote if you want a hand. In a tightly built heritage
          street, the right scheme lifts the whole row.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Damp climate, careful interiors.</h3>
        <p>
          New Town&rsquo;s cool, often-shaded blocks stay damp, so exterior prep
          starts with a proper wash and mould treatment. Inside, we use low-VOC
          paints (better in a closed-up winter home), protect original
          floorboards and features, and keep lead-safe practice indoors where
          sanding old trim could release dust. See
          <a href="/services/interior-painting/">interior house painting</a> and
          <a href="/services/exterior-painting/">exterior house painting</a>.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Typical New Town jobs.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Full heritage repaint of a Federation or Georgian home, period-correct scheme</li>
          <li>Lead-safe exterior repaint of pre-1970 weatherboard with detailed trim</li>
          <li>Interior repaint with careful protection of original floors and joinery</li>
          <li>Fretwork, fascia and window-joinery restoration and repaint</li>
          <li>Roof clean and recoat sympathetic to a heritage streetscape</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <h2>Other service areas.</h2>
      <div class="areas-grid">
        <a class="area-pill" href="/sandy-bay/">Sandy Bay</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/glenorchy/">Glenorchy</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/kingston/">Kingston</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/moonah/">Moonah</a>
        <a class="area-pill" href="/hobart-region/">All Greater Hobart</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Free New Town painting quote.</h2>
        <p>Heritage precinct specialists. Lead-safe prep, conservation-sensitive finish, period-correct colour.</p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="ph-cta btn btn-primary" href="/quote/" aria-label="Call us"><span aria-hidden="true">&#9742;</span> <span class="ph-text">Tap to call</span></a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book online</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
